<subSubSection lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="117" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1728,2043]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1800,1826]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Differs from the nominate subspecies by longer tegmina, from other 
<taxonomicName box="[1142,1352,1800,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[1142,1260,1800,1826]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Mecopoda</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the characteristic amplitude modulation in the trill (see 
<figureCitation box="[742,839,1836,1863]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 6" captionStart-1="FIGURE 7" captionStartId-0="14.[151,250,1523,1547]" captionStartId-1="15.[151,250,1478,1502]" captionTargetBox-0="[160,1425,192,1493]" captionTargetBox-1="[161,1429,186,1446]" captionTargetId-0="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1499]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@15.[151,1436,181,1454]" captionTargetPageId-0="14" captionTargetPageId-1="15" captionText-0="FIGURE 6. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda niponensis subgroup and of M. cf. yunnana. Overview (12 s sections)." captionText-1="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda niponensis subgroup. Details (1 s sections). In M. himalaya synchronous registration of movement of left tegmen and sound (upper line: upward deflection indicating opening, downward closing; lower line: sound)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141295" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141297" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5141295/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5141297/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Fig. 6–7</figureCitation>
) and from the Vietnamese species 
<taxonomicName box="[1239,1348,1836,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ampla">
<emphasis box="[1239,1348,1836,1862]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">M. ampla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gorochov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prominens">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">M. prominens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in file structure (see 
<figureCitation box="[506,629,1872,1898]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 11" captionStart-1="FIGURE 12" captionStartId-0="20.[151,250,1772,1796]" captionStartId-1="21.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox-0="[217,1370,181,1747]" captionTargetBox-1="[307,1292,191,1912]" captionTargetId-0="figure-27@20.[217,1370,181,1747]" captionTargetId-1="figure-19@21.[291,1297,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId-0="20" captionTargetPageId-1="21" captionText-0="FIGURE 11. Stridulatory files in Mecopoda and Eumecopoda. A M. niponensis niponensis, lectotype, B M. niponensis vietnamica subsp. nov., holotype, C M. himalaya, CH3737 (Malaysia), D M. himalaya (=M. ampla malayensis, holotype), E M. himalaya (=M. ampla javaensis, holotype), F M. himalaya (=M. fallax aequatorialis, holotype), G M. macassariensis, holotype, H M. fallax, Thailand, I M. stridulata stridulata, CRTmeceloM02 (Borneo), J M. stridulata stridulata, holotype, K M. paucidens sp. nov., (Java), L M. sismondoi sp. nov., holotype, M M. javana, neotype, N M. javana, Sri Lanka, O M. mahindai sp. nov., holotype, P M. angusta, CH3697, Q M. dilatata, ORT 2005/413 (Borneo), R E. cyrtoscelis zhantievi subsp. nov., holotype, S M. prominens, holotype, T M. ampla ampla, holotype. Scale 1 mm." captionText-1="FIGURE 12. Inter-tooth spacing in stridulatory files of Mecopoda species. Thick lines and filled symbols indicate specimens with known song. A–D: M. elongata group: A M. niponensis subgroup and M. marmorata, B M. himalaya and macassariensis, C M. fallax and species with similar files, D M. confracta subgroup, E other Mecopoda and Eumecopoda species." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141307" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141309" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5141307/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5141309/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Fig. 11–12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1728,2043]" box="[199,1054,1908,1935]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1908,1934]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Morphology.</emphasis>
As nominate subspecies, but with longer tegmina (see above).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1728,2043]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1437,151,646]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="117" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,265,1944,1970]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Song.</emphasis>
The recorded specimen had an unusually variable song containing two elements. It produced trill-like series, quite similar to the song of the continental subspecies (
<figureCitation box="[839,905,1980,2007]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1523,1547]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,192,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-27@14.[151,1436,181,1499]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 6. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda niponensis subgroup and of M. cf. yunnana. Overview (12 s sections)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141295" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141295/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) and to that known from other parts of its range (for details see Liu Cx 
<emphasis box="[409,466,2016,2042]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">et al.</emphasis>
2020). These series last for many minutes and have a relatively complicated structure. Within a song unit, the low-amplitude beginning and ending phases consist of repeated simple syllables, while the high-amplitude climax is composed of many repeated subunits. In the recorded specimen the subunits consisted of five to six syllables with a characteristic amplitude pattern (
<figureCitation box="[821,889,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1478,1502]" captionTargetBox="[161,1429,186,1446]" captionTargetId="figure-19@15.[151,1436,181,1454]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 7. Oscillograms of the calling songs of species of the Mecopoda niponensis subgroup. Details (1 s sections). In M. himalaya synchronous registration of movement of left tegmen and sound (upper line: upward deflection indicating opening, downward closing; lower line: sound)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141297/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). In other parts of its range like 
<collectingCountry box="[1249,1313,223,249]" name="Japan" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Japan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1436,223,249]" name="South Korea" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[161,309,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">
n. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Haan" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[189,309,259,284]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niponensis">niponensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) one subunit seems to have typically only three syllables (
<bibRefCitation author="Ichikawa, A. &amp; Ito, F. &amp; Kano, Y. &amp; Kawai, M. &amp; Tominaga, O. &amp; Murai, T." box="[966,1201,259,285]" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" refId="ref24878" refString="Ichikawa, A., Ito, F., Kano, Y., Kawai, M., Tominaga, O. &amp; Murai, T. (Eds.) (2006) Orthoptera of the Japanese Archipelago in color. s. n., Sapporo, 688 pp. + 2 CD." type="book" year="2006">
Ichikawa 
<emphasis box="[1078,1134,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kim, T. W." box="[1212,1330,259,285]" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" refId="ref25205" refString="Kim, T. W. (2009) Taxonomy and acoustic signals of Korean Tettigonioidea (Orthoptera: Ensifera) II. National Institut of Biological Reserves, Incheon. [+ CD]" type="book" year="2009">Kim 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Besides the trills, the specimen produced also occasionally long series of echemes before the trill. In the frequency spectrum, the ultrasound components were even stronger than the peak in the audible range (
<figureCitation box="[1073,1157,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="24.[151,250,953,977]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,244,924]" captionTargetId="figure-44@24.[151,1436,237,929]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 14. Power spectra of the calling songs of Mecopoda species. In A, red line trill, green line chirp; in B–D, grey area opening and closing hemisyllable together, blue line opening hemisyllable only, yellow line closing hemisyllable only (for Eumecopoda opening/closing assumed)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141313" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141313/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,151,646]" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,401,366,392]" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Stridulatory file.</emphasis>
Like specimens of the nominate subspecies, also the Vietnamese specimen has a long file carrying about 115 teeth (
<figureCitation box="[449,560,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1772,1796]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-27@20.[217,1370,181,1747]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 11. Stridulatory files in Mecopoda and Eumecopoda. A M. niponensis niponensis, lectotype, B M. niponensis vietnamica subsp. nov., holotype, C M. himalaya, CH3737 (Malaysia), D M. himalaya (=M. ampla malayensis, holotype), E M. himalaya (=M. ampla javaensis, holotype), F M. himalaya (=M. fallax aequatorialis, holotype), G M. macassariensis, holotype, H M. fallax, Thailand, I M. stridulata stridulata, CRTmeceloM02 (Borneo), J M. stridulata stridulata, holotype, K M. paucidens sp. nov., (Java), L M. sismondoi sp. nov., holotype, M M. javana, neotype, N M. javana, Sri Lanka, O M. mahindai sp. nov., holotype, P M. angusta, CH3697, Q M. dilatata, ORT 2005/413 (Borneo), R E. cyrtoscelis zhantievi subsp. nov., holotype, S M. prominens, holotype, T M. ampla ampla, holotype. Scale 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141307" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141307/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Fig. 11 B</figureCitation>
) like 
<emphasis box="[630,810,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">
M. n. 
<taxonomicName box="[701,810,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niponenis">niponenis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. The inter-teeth distances start anally with 50 µm and reach their maximum of about 80 µm between the 30th and 40th tooth (
<figureCitation box="[950,1032,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[307,1292,191,1912]" captionTargetId="figure-19@21.[291,1297,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 12. Inter-tooth spacing in stridulatory files of Mecopoda species. Thick lines and filled symbols indicate specimens with known song. A–D: M. elongata group: A M. niponensis subgroup and M. marmorata, B M. himalaya and macassariensis, C M. fallax and species with similar files, D M. confracta subgroup, E other Mecopoda and Eumecopoda species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5141309" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5141309/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). In the file of the 
<typeStatus box="[1239,1342,439,465]" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">
M. n. 
<taxonomicName box="[151,260,475,500]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Mecopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niponenis">niponenis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
the inter-tooth distances are slightly smaller but there is some variability in this character. The file of the 
<emphasis box="[151,361,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="117">M. n. continentalis</emphasis>
specimen (105 teeth) photographed by Liu Cx 
